<center><table border=0><tr><td><center><H2><font face=arial>Re: Answers for naked rampaging mages</font></H2></center>
<font face=arial size=2><b>Posted By:</b> <A HREF="/cgi-local/whois2.cgi?Vulpine">Vulpine</a><br>
<b>Posted On:</b> 1:07 a.m. 10/6/1999<br>
<b>Subject:</b> Re: Answers for naked rampaging mages<p>
<br><center><img src="http://www.everworld.net/pvpquest/images/divider.gif" width=452 height=22 border=0></center><BR><P ALIGN=CENTER><b>In Reply To:</b> <A HREF="http://www.everworld.net/cgi-local/pvp.cgi?read=2166" TARGET=_self>Answers for naked rampaging mages</A> (TheBlack)
</STRONG><FONT SIZE=2 color=#FFFFFF FACE=arial>
<P>I think the problem with your solution(s) is that it weakens mages in general. My solution does not affect how mages play at all - it *only* affects them in PK/death situations.

<P>Mages in non-PK situations are hard enough already, IMHO.
<P>Ciao...
<P>&gt; First solution is to make it so you come back from death with no
<BR>&gt; mana. I've already asked Brad to put this in on Rallos Zek.
<P>&gt; The second solution is a bit more involved. Mages could be
<BR>&gt; required to purchase magical items, call them foci, that are
<BR>&gt; required for charging mana. Without one you could limit the
<BR>&gt; amount of total mana to 50% of maximum. A lesser foci might give
<BR>&gt; you 80%, a regular 100%, and a powerful quest foci perhaps 110%
<BR>&gt; or more. These foci could take the fom of just about anything (a
<BR>&gt; magical gem for example), but they should be lootable. To make
<BR>&gt; them lootable we could require they remain in one's inventory
<BR>&gt; and be non-equippable, and change looting rules so that only
<BR>&gt; items in the inventory can be looted. The cost of replacing a
<BR>&gt; foci should be similar to what a warrior pays for a decent
<BR>&gt; weapon or a small piece of armor.
<P>&gt; Another way to place a foci would be to require it be eqiupped
<BR>&gt; by use of a spell. To unequip it would also require the use of a
<BR>&gt; slow to cast high-mana use spell. In this fashion the item would
<BR>&gt; most likely be equipped at the time of the mage's death.
<BR>
</FONT></td></tr></table></P>
